1
00:01:17,177 --> 00:01:19,168
Hey, Sheriff.

2
00:01:26,820 --> 00:01:28,811
("Chair scraping on floor)

3
00:02:29,282 --> 00:02:33,412
A Mercury is a real good car.

4
00:02:33,486 --> 00:02:36,683
That was the car I was driving that day.

5
00:02:39,692 --> 00:02:42,024
I have a lot of cars.

6
00:02:43,029 --> 00:02:45,361
Yeah. Different kinds.

7
00:02:46,599 --> 00:02:49,261
A lot of different kinds of cars.

8
00:02:50,370 --> 00:02:53,305
She was standing, this girl,

9
00:02:54,307 --> 00:02:56,537
on the side of the street
where there was this chicken stand.

10
00:02:56,609 --> 00:02:58,941
It wasn't the Colonel,
but it was a chicken stand nevertheless.

11
00:02:59,012 --> 00:03:01,981
And I pulled the Mercury right up alongside

12
00:03:02,048 --> 00:03:05,484
and I rolled down the window,
see, by electric power.

13
00:03:05,552 --> 00:03:09,716
And she had this leather skirt on.

14
00:03:09,789 --> 00:03:12,781
And she had a lot of hair on her arms.

15
00:03:12,859 --> 00:03:18,855
I like hair, I like hair a lot.
It means a big bush. I like a big bush.

16
00:03:19,732 --> 00:03:24,829
So she says, "Are you dating?" You know?

17
00:03:24,904 --> 00:03:27,099
I said, "Sure." So she gets in.

18
00:03:27,173 --> 00:03:32,440
And we pull off
into this remote location, you know,

19
00:03:32,512 --> 00:03:34,776
that was comfortable for both she and I.

20
00:03:34,847 --> 00:03:38,214
And she says to me,
"How much do you wanna spend?"

21
00:03:38,284 --> 00:03:41,913
And I said, "Whatever it takes to see that
bush of yours, 'cause I know it's a big one."

22
00:03:41,988 --> 00:03:44,980
And she says to me, "25 dollars."

23
00:03:47,093 --> 00:03:52,030
That's not chicken feed, you know...
to a working man.

24
00:03:52,098 --> 00:03:57,434
So I produce the 25 dollars and she sticks
it down into her shoe and pulls up her skirt.

25
00:03:57,503 --> 00:04:00,904
And there before me lay this thin,

26
00:04:00,974 --> 00:04:03,966
crooked, uncircumcised penis.

27
00:04:09,182 --> 00:04:13,585
You can imagine how bad
I wanted my 25 dollars back, huh?

28
00:04:17,123 --> 00:04:20,718
("Girl) I don't know why you're
so weirded out. This is not San Quentin.

29
00:04:20,793 --> 00:04:23,489
It's just a nut house. Most of these people
don't even know where they are.

30
00:04:23,563 --> 00:04:25,053
They're not gonna hurt you.

31
00:04:25,131 --> 00:04:28,294
In a few minutes, we're gonna be in a room
with a killer. That doesn't bother you?

32
00:04:28,368 --> 00:04:30,996
Hey, you're the one
that wanted to major in journalism.

33
00:04:36,409 --> 00:04:38,570
These are the people
from that newspaper deal.

34
00:04:38,645 --> 00:04:41,136
- Oh, yeah. From the college?
- Yes, sir.

35
00:04:41,214 --> 00:04:43,205
- I'm Jerry Woolridge.
- Nice to meet you.

36
00:04:43,283 --> 00:04:45,649
I'm Marsha Dwiggins
and this is Theresa Evans.

37
00:04:45,718 --> 00:04:48,448
She's here to take the pictures.

38
00:04:48,521 --> 00:04:50,853
Y'all sit down.

39
00:04:51,891 --> 00:04:54,121
Yeah, there was a young man
named John Legit Hunter

40
00:04:54,193 --> 00:04:56,957
who was in the filling station business -
a good filling station business.

41
00:04:57,030 --> 00:04:59,362
But he was one of these young men
we run across in life,

42
00:04:59,432 --> 00:05:02,833
I'm sure you've run across 'em, who didn't
deserve what he had, you know?

43
00:05:02,902 --> 00:05:07,202
And one of the things he had was this...

44
00:05:07,273 --> 00:05:09,264
beautiful young bride,

45
00:05:09,342 --> 00:05:12,106
Sarah.

46
00:05:12,178 --> 00:05:14,078
She was a Georgia peach.

47
00:05:14,147 --> 00:05:19,949
In fact, she was more like the picture I had
in my mind than any woman I'd ever seen.

48
00:05:20,019 --> 00:05:23,477
So I took it upon myself
to take her away from John Legit Hunter,

49
00:05:23,556 --> 00:05:26,457
who did not deserve her, you know?

50
00:05:26,526 --> 00:05:29,620
Oh, I don't know if I told you,

51
00:05:29,696 --> 00:05:34,258
but he was a Frenchman
who claimed to be an Englishman.

52
00:05:36,602 --> 00:05:39,662
Yeah... Took a lot of strong nylon cord
to get her away from him,

53
00:05:39,739 --> 00:05:44,472
'cause she was a fighter
as well as being a Georgia peach.

54
00:05:46,946 --> 00:05:50,939
I think there must have been a little mix-up.

55
00:05:51,017 --> 00:05:53,986
I talked to your sponsor or teacher,
or whoever he is,

56
00:05:54,053 --> 00:05:57,489
and I told him that
there couldn't be any pictures.

57
00:05:57,557 --> 00:06:02,961
It's supposed to be like an article or a
story, something like that, isn't that right?

58
00:06:03,029 --> 00:06:06,362
Well, yeah, it's for the school newspaper,
but it has pictures.

59
00:06:06,432 --> 00:06:08,764
I mean, it's a regular paper, you know?

60
00:06:08,835 --> 00:06:11,360
Karl's real sensitive
about having his picture made.

61
00:06:11,437 --> 00:06:14,873
He wouldn't even be on the bulletin board
for the Easter collage.

62
00:06:18,077 --> 00:06:20,841
Now...

63
00:06:20,913 --> 00:06:24,508
a shovel just makes
too goddamn much racket.

64
00:06:33,159 --> 00:06:36,856
All I can do is talk to him,
see what he says.

65
00:06:38,431 --> 00:06:40,922
You gotta make something explode
to truly understand it.

66
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:46,996
I mean, you gotta examine all those little
tiny particles while they're still on fire.

67
00:06:47,073 --> 00:06:50,065
("Guard) Karl, I've gotta take you
down to the old classroom.

68
00:06:50,143 --> 00:06:55,046
Mr. Woolridge has some people
for you to see down there.

69
00:06:55,114 --> 00:06:57,275
Come on, let's go.

70
00:07:15,468 --> 00:07:18,995
You remember me telling you
about those people from that newspaper?

71
00:07:19,071 --> 00:07:22,199
They wanna ask you some questions
about your release.

72
00:07:22,275 --> 00:07:25,108
They think it'll make a good story.

73
00:07:25,178 --> 00:07:28,375
Will you talk to 'em?
Get interviewed?

74
00:07:30,249 --> 00:07:32,376
- Now, they're women.
- ("Guard snorts.)

75
00:07:35,488 --> 00:07:38,480
I think it'd be good for you, too.
You're gonna be seeing all kinds of people

76
00:07:38,558 --> 00:07:40,890
when you get on the outside.

77
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:43,292
This'll help, I believe.

78
00:07:49,969 --> 00:07:53,097
Now, here's the thing.
He'll only talk to you,

79
00:07:53,172 --> 00:07:55,299
but he doesn't want
you to ask him anything.

80
00:07:55,374 --> 00:07:57,365
And you really shouldn't stare at him.

81
00:07:57,443 --> 00:07:59,877
How am I going to conduct an interview
if I can't ask him any questions?

82
00:07:59,946 --> 00:08:02,244
It's the best it's gonna get. I'm sorry.

83
00:08:02,315 --> 00:08:07,378
Can I ask you a question? If he's so
troubled, why are you letting him out?

84
00:08:07,453 --> 00:08:10,183
What if he does it again?
It happens all the time.

85
00:08:10,256 --> 00:08:12,952
He's free, his time's up.
That's the rules.

86
00:08:13,025 --> 00:08:16,620
He's been treated and reevaluated
and doesn't show any signs anymore.

87
00:08:16,696 --> 00:08:19,426
- Signs?
- Homicidal signs.

88
00:08:19,499 --> 00:08:24,698
Oh, Miss. I'm sorry,
but you're gonna have to step outside.

89
00:08:24,770 --> 00:08:26,601
Why?

90
00:08:26,672 --> 00:08:28,503
Please?

91
00:08:37,350 --> 00:08:40,751
I gotta change the light in here for Karl.

92
00:08:40,820 --> 00:08:43,516
I hope you can still see to write.

93
00:09:24,697 --> 00:09:28,861
I reckon what you is wanting to know
is what I'm a-doin' in here.

94
00:09:28,935 --> 00:09:34,134
I reckon the reason I'm in here
is 'cause I've killed somebody. Mm-hm.

95
00:09:34,206 --> 00:09:37,835
But I reckon what you is a-wantin' to know
is how come me to kill somebody,

96
00:09:37,910 --> 00:09:41,744
so I reckon I'll start at the front and tell you.

97
00:09:43,716 --> 00:09:48,710
I lived out the back of my mother
and father's place most of my life,

98
00:09:48,788 --> 00:09:52,554
in a little old shed
that my daddy had built for me.

99
00:09:52,625 --> 00:09:56,959
They didn't too much want me
up there in the house with the rest of 'em.

100
00:09:57,029 --> 00:10:02,661
So mostly, I just sat around out there
in the shed, a-lookin' at the ground.

101
00:10:02,735 --> 00:10:05,636
I didn't have no floor out there.

102
00:10:05,705 --> 00:10:09,869
But I had me a hole dug out to lay down in.

103
00:10:09,942 --> 00:10:12,934
A quilt or two to put down there. Mm-hm.

104
00:10:15,548 --> 00:10:20,576
My father was a hardworking man
most of his life.

105
00:10:20,653 --> 00:10:24,282
Not that I can say the same for myself.

106
00:10:24,357 --> 00:10:26,723
I mostly just sat around
out there in the shed,

107
00:10:26,792 --> 00:10:30,057
tinkered around with a lawn mower or two.

108
00:10:30,129 --> 00:10:33,792
Went to school off and on
from time to time.

109
00:10:33,866 --> 00:10:39,099
But the children out there,
they were very cruel to me.

110
00:10:39,171 --> 00:10:43,608
Made quite a bit of sport of me.
Made fun of me quite a bit.

111
00:10:43,676 --> 00:10:49,342
So mostly, I just sat around
out there in the shed.

112
00:10:52,652 --> 00:10:56,679
My daddy worked down there
at the saw mill,

113
00:10:56,756 --> 00:11:00,658
down at the planer mill
for an old man named Dixon.

114
00:11:00,726 --> 00:11:03,251
Old man Dixon was a very cruel fella.

115
00:11:03,329 --> 00:11:06,765
Didn't treat his employees very well.
Didn't pay 'em too much of a wage.

116
00:11:06,832 --> 00:11:09,665
Didn't pay my daddy too much of a wage.

117
00:11:09,735 --> 00:11:13,501
Just barely enough to get by on, I reckon.

118
00:11:13,572 --> 00:11:16,234
But I reckon he got by all right.

119
00:11:18,744 --> 00:11:22,612
They used to come out,
one or the other of 'em,

120
00:11:22,682 --> 00:11:24,877
usually my mother,

121
00:11:24,950 --> 00:11:27,214
feed me pretty regular.

122
00:11:28,220 --> 00:11:30,279
Though I know he made enough
to where I could have

123
00:11:30,356 --> 00:11:34,224
mustard and biscuits
three or four times a week.

124
00:11:37,196 --> 00:11:40,859
But old man Dixon, he had a boy.

125
00:11:42,802 --> 00:11:45,532
His name was Jesse Dixon.

126
00:11:45,604 --> 00:11:49,335
Jesse was really more cruel
than his daddy was.

127
00:11:49,408 --> 00:11:55,404
He used to make quite a bit of sport of me
when I was down there at the schoolhouse.

128
00:11:58,150 --> 00:12:04,146
He used to take advantage of little girls
there in the neighborhood an' all.

129
00:12:05,324 --> 00:12:11,092
He used to say that my mother
was a very pretty woman.

130
00:12:11,163 --> 00:12:16,430
He said that quite a bit from time to time
when I'd be down there at the schoolhouse.

131
00:12:16,502 --> 00:12:18,470
Well...

132
00:12:18,537 --> 00:12:21,563
I reckon you want me to get on with it
and tell you what happened,

133
00:12:21,640 --> 00:12:23,870
so I reckon I'll tell you.

134
00:12:24,877 --> 00:12:28,244
I was sittin' out there in the shed one
evening, not doing too much of nothing,

135
00:12:28,314 --> 00:12:30,976
just kinda staring at the wall,

136
00:12:31,050 --> 00:12:35,987
waiting on my mother to come out
and give me my Bible lesson.

137
00:12:37,423 --> 00:12:41,052
Well, I heard a commotion
up there in the house.

138
00:12:41,127 --> 00:12:44,824
So I run up on the screened-in porch
to see what was a-goin' on.

139
00:12:44,897 --> 00:12:47,764
I looked in the window there
and I seen my mother laying on the floor,

140
00:12:47,833 --> 00:12:50,358
without any clothes on.

141
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:52,427
Mm-hm.

142
00:12:55,775 --> 00:12:58,972
I seen Jesse Dixon a-layin' on top of her.

143
00:13:01,647 --> 00:13:04,138
He was having his way with her.

144
00:13:05,417 --> 00:13:07,749
Well, I just seen red.

145
00:13:11,423 --> 00:13:15,291
I picked up a Kaiser blade
that was sitting there by the screen door.

146
00:13:15,361 --> 00:13:19,593
Some folks call it a sling blade,
I call it a Kaiser blade.

147
00:13:19,665 --> 00:13:23,601
It's got a long wood handle,
kind of like an axe handle.

148
00:13:23,669 --> 00:13:27,867
With a long blade on it
shaped kind of like a banana. Mm-hm.

149
00:13:27,940 --> 00:13:31,637
Sharp on one edge and dull on the other.

150
00:13:31,710 --> 00:13:36,704
It's what the highway boys use
to cut down weeds and whatnot.

151
00:13:39,018 --> 00:13:41,953
Well, I went in there in the house,

152
00:13:42,021 --> 00:13:47,254
and I hit Jesse Dixon upside the head
with it, knocked him off my mother.

153
00:13:48,260 --> 00:13:51,423
I reckon that didn't quite satisfy me.

154
00:13:53,265 --> 00:13:56,029
So I hit him again with it in the neck
with the sharp edge

155
00:13:56,101 --> 00:14:00,128
and just plumb near cut his head off,
killed him.

156
00:14:02,274 --> 00:14:04,765
My mother, she jumped up from there
and started hollerin':

157
00:14:04,844 --> 00:14:07,836
"What did you kill Jesse for?
What did you kill Jesse for?"

158
00:14:07,913 --> 00:14:09,778
Well...

159
00:14:09,849 --> 00:14:15,287
Come to find out I don't reckon my mother
minded what Jesse was a-doin' to her.

160
00:14:15,354 --> 00:14:19,256
I reckon that made me madder
than what Jesse had made me.

161
00:14:19,325 --> 00:14:21,657
So I taken the Kaiser blade,

162
00:14:21,727 --> 00:14:26,255
some folks call it a sling blade,
I call it a Kaiser blade,

163
00:14:27,266 --> 00:14:31,293
and I hit my mother
upside the head with it.

164
00:14:33,272 --> 00:14:34,933
Killed her.

165
00:14:39,511 --> 00:14:41,638
Some folks has asked me:

166
00:14:41,714 --> 00:14:45,650
"If you had it to do over again,
would you do it the same way?"

167
00:14:45,718 --> 00:14:48,050
Well, I reckon I would.

168
00:14:49,388 --> 00:14:55,384
Anyhow, they seen fit to put me in here,
and here I've been for a great long while.

169
00:14:57,563 --> 00:14:59,895
I've learned to read some.

170
00:15:00,799 --> 00:15:04,235
Took me four years to read the Bible.

171
00:15:04,303 --> 00:15:07,363
I reckon I understand a great deal of it.

172
00:15:07,439 --> 00:15:10,636
Wasn't what I expected in some places.

173
00:15:12,411 --> 00:15:16,211
I've slept in a good bed
for a great long while.

174
00:15:17,416 --> 00:15:19,816
Now they've seen fit to put me out of here.

175
00:15:19,885 --> 00:15:23,218
They say they're setting me free today.

176
00:15:26,025 --> 00:15:29,756
Anyhow, I reckon
that's all you'd need to know.

177
00:15:30,562 --> 00:15:34,498
If you wanna hear about more details,
I reckon I can tell 'em to you.

178
00:15:34,566 --> 00:15:39,196
I don't know whether or not that's enough
for your newspaper or not. Mm-hm.

179
00:15:39,271 --> 00:15:43,401
("Marsha.) Will you ever
kill anybody again, Karl?

180
00:15:53,218 --> 00:15:57,245
I don't reckon
I've got no reason to kill nobody.

181
00:16:06,632 --> 00:16:09,260
- Where will he go?
- Anywhere he wants to.

182
00:16:09,335 --> 00:16:11,326
I think he's going back to Millsberg,
where he's from.

183
00:16:11,403 --> 00:16:14,736
- It's just about 20 miles from here.
- Will he be supervised?

184
00:16:14,807 --> 00:16:17,105
As much as anybody else is, I guess.

185
00:16:17,176 --> 00:16:20,339
Y'all have a real nice rest of the day, now.

186
00:16:20,412 --> 00:16:23,245
I'll get Melvin to walk y'all out.

187
00:16:27,486 --> 00:16:31,513
Melvin, could you
walk these girls out, please?

188
00:16:32,124 --> 00:16:33,955
Thank you.

189
00:16:34,026 --> 00:16:35,857
Thank you.

190
00:16:46,105 --> 00:16:50,337
I reckon I'm gonna have to get used
to looking at purdy people. Mm-hm.

191
00:16:50,409 --> 00:16:52,570
I guess you will.

192
00:16:53,512 --> 00:16:58,882
I reckon I'm gonna have to get used
to them looking at me, too.

193
00:16:58,951 --> 00:17:01,442
Better go get your things.

194
00:17:01,520 --> 00:17:04,421
I ain't got nothing but them books.

195
00:17:05,491 --> 00:17:07,652
Better go get 'em.

196
00:17:08,527 --> 00:17:10,518
All right, then.

197
00:17:22,508 --> 00:17:24,499
All right, then.

198
00:20:21,086 --> 00:20:23,316
Can I help you, sir?

199
00:20:26,959 --> 00:20:29,257
Can I help you, sir?

200
00:20:29,928 --> 00:20:33,091
I was kindly wanting
something or other to eat. Mm-hm.

201
00:20:33,165 --> 00:20:35,497
Well, what would you like?

202
00:20:37,269 --> 00:20:40,067
You got any biscuits for sale in there?

203
00:20:40,138 --> 00:20:43,835
No, this here's a Frostee Cream.
We don't serve biscuits.

204
00:20:43,909 --> 00:20:48,107
- We got a lot of other stuff, though.
- What you got in there that's good to eat?

205
00:20:48,180 --> 00:20:52,480
Well, we got Big Chief burgers,
Bongo burgers, Footlongs, Corny Dogs,

206
00:20:52,551 --> 00:20:55,179
Frostee Shakes, Creamy Bars.

207
00:20:55,254 --> 00:20:58,223
Did you want me
to go through the whole list?

208
00:20:58,290 --> 00:21:00,815
Reckon what do you like to eat in there?

209
00:21:02,261 --> 00:21:04,627
Well...

210
00:21:04,696 --> 00:21:07,631
The French fries are pretty good.

211
00:21:07,699 --> 00:21:11,499
- French-fried potatoes?
- Yep, French fries.

212
00:21:14,172 --> 00:21:16,106
How much you want for 'em?

213
00:21:16,174 --> 00:21:20,167
Well, they're 60 for the medium
and 75 for the large.

214
00:21:23,282 --> 00:21:25,978
I reckon I'll have me some of the big 'uns.

215
00:21:26,051 --> 00:21:29,452
All right, then. One large French fries.

216
00:22:09,828 --> 00:22:14,197
These darn things are heavy.
Hard to carry, too.

217
00:22:14,266 --> 00:22:17,667
- What you got in there, wash?
- Yeah.

218
00:22:18,670 --> 00:22:21,730
Ain't you got no mom and daddy
to tend to it?

219
00:22:21,807 --> 00:22:26,540
I got a momma. She's at work
over at Hoochy's Dollar Store.

220
00:22:26,611 --> 00:22:29,842
Daddy's dead.
He got hit by a train.

221
00:22:32,551 --> 00:22:35,452
How far are you going
with them sacks full of wash?

222
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:37,852
Half a mile, I think it is.

223
00:22:39,091 --> 00:22:41,992
I can help you tote it
if I don't give out first.

224
00:22:42,060 --> 00:22:44,722
OK, but you don't have to.

225
00:22:46,765 --> 00:22:48,733
All right, then.

226
00:22:51,603 --> 00:22:54,697
My name's Frank Wheatley.
What's your name?

227
00:22:54,773 --> 00:22:57,071
Karl's my name.

228
00:22:57,142 --> 00:23:00,134
- What's your last name?
- Childers.

229
00:23:01,480 --> 00:23:03,675
What are all them books?

230
00:23:03,749 --> 00:23:05,740
All different ones.

231
